Prakash - you raise an interesting question: how do you approach a mentor?  If you approach a complete stranger and say, &quot;I&#039;d like you to mentor me,&quot; you probably won&#039;t get a positive response.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
As somebody who does a lot of mentoring, I can say that it&#039;s definitely a two-way street.  Before I begin a mentoring relationship, I want to see that the person has already taken initiative to contribute in the community.  That might be blogging, helping out in forums, speaking at events, answering #SQLHelp questions, or even just being part of a dialog on Twitter.  If someone hasn&#039;t done any of those things, I don&#039;t see them as really serious about giving back - only taking.  In that case, I personally say no.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I&#039;d suggest opening your requests by talking about the work you&#039;ve done so far for the community, and then ask for help taking things to the next level.  By laying out the work you&#039;ve already done, you can remind your potential mentor that yes, you ARE active even if they don&#039;t remember your name offhand.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Hope that helps!

